            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Veronica Reyes was a product of San Francisco\u2019s grittier, blue-collar past. Raised in a small Sunset District row house by a firefighter father and a stay-at-home mother, she was taught the value of a steady hand and a strong work ethic over academic prestige. She enrolled in community college for Business Administration with a vague plan to manage a small business, but her life\u2019s trajectory was permanently altered when she met Marco Reyes, a charismatic apprentice electrician.\n\nTheir whirlwind romance led to an unexpected pregnancy. Prioritizing family, Veronica left school to take an entry-level assembly job at a small electronics manufacturing company in the Dogpatch, providing a steady income while Marco finished his training. For fifteen years, they built a life, raising their son, Mateo, in a rented Potrero Hill apartment. Marco\u2019s sudden death from a heart attack when she was just 38 was a seismic shock.\n\nGrief became fuel. As a single mother, Veronica poured her energy into her work, the one thing she could control. She learned every machine, streamlined every process, and earned the respect of her colleagues with her no-nonsense fairness. She climbed from the line to team lead, and eventually to Production Floor Manager, her \u201csome college\u201d education eclipsed by two decades of hard-won experience.\n\nNow, at 51, Veronica\u2019s life is one of disciplined routine. Her mornings start with coffee on her small balcony overlooking the bay, followed by a brisk walk to the 19-Polk bus for the short ride to work. She knows her team not just as employees, but as people, remembering their kids' names and weekend plans. Her social life is modest, consisting of weekly dinners with her son, now a graphic designer in Oakland, and occasional drinks with her lead mechanics. She has watched the city transform around her, from a haven for working-class families to a playground for the tech elite, holding onto her rent-controlled apartment as a relic of a bygone era.\n\nHer dream is no longer about climbing a corporate ladder. It\u2019s simpler: to save enough to finally take a trip to Spain. It\u2019s more than a vacation; it\u2019s a chance to explore a culture tied to the name she carried for a lifetime, to travel not as a wife or a mother, but purely as herself."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was twenty, leaning against Marco\u2019s beat-up Ford Falcon outside the community college. He still smelled faintly of solder and sweat from work, his hands calloused and sure as he described wiring a new building. He wasn\u2019t promising a fancy life, just a steady one. Looking at the raw certainty in a man who built things, she felt her own vague academic plans dissolve. That feeling\u2014a terrifying, thrilling freefall\u2014was the moment her life truly began, rerouting her entire future for a love that felt as tangible as electricity.\n\n2.\nMateo was six, sprawled on the living room floor of their Potrero Hill apartment, meticulously \u201cfixing\u201d a broken lamp with Marco's real screwdrivers. From the kitchen, the smell of her mother's adobo recipe filled the small space as the lights of the container ships blinked across the bay. It wasn't a life of wealth, but in that moment of shared, easy purpose and the city humming below, she felt a profound sense of rightness. This small world they built, contained within these walls, was perfect.\n\n3.\nThe day after Marco died, she stood in the kitchen\u2019s stark morning light, automatically reaching for two coffee mugs. The sight of her own hand, stopping mid-air, was what broke her. It wasn\u2019t a wave of grief but a sudden, hollow clarity. There was no one to make coffee for. No one to remind about a dentist appointment. In that suffocating silence, the sheer, crushing weight of every single future detail fell on her. That was the moment she stopped being a wife and became a survivor.\n\n4.\nThe main conveyor belt seized during a critical rush order. The company engineer was useless, talking about schematics. Veronica, then a team lead, simply put her hand on the motor housing, closing her eyes. She knew its rhythm, its groans. She remembered a similar jam from five years prior, grabbing a wrench and making a crude adjustment another mechanic had once shown her. The belt lurched back to life. The weary, respectful nod from the head mechanic was more validating than any formal promotion she would ever receive.\n\n5.\nLast month, over dinner in Oakland, Mateo was excitedly explaining a new branding project, his passion for his work lighting up his face. She saw Marco's easy charm in his smile, but the fierce work ethic was all hers. Suddenly, she didn\u2019t see the boy she had to raise, but the man he had become\u2014her greatest project, now complete. A quiet space opened up in her mind, a space she realized was finally, purely, her own. Spain felt less like a dream and more like the next job."
